{"title_page": "Avril Lavigne discography", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist discography\n|Artist          = [[Avril Lavigne]]\n|Image           = File:Avril Lavigne @ The Greek 09 18 2019 (49311431362).jpg\n|Caption         = Avril Lavigne performing live at The Greek Theatre in [[Los Angeles]] in September 2019.\n|Studio          = 6\n|Live            = 1\n|EP              = 8\n|Singles         = 28\n|Option          = 17\n|Option name     = Promotional singles\n|Music videos    = 29\n}}\n\nCanadian singer-songwriter [[Avril Lavigne]] has released 6 [[studio album]]s, 8 [[extended play]]s, 28 singles, and 29 music videos, and she has appeared on several [[soundtrack|movie soundtracks]] and [[charity record|charity albums]].\n\nLavigne's debut studio album ''[[Let Go (Avril Lavigne album)|Let Go]]'' was released in June 2002 and peaked at number two on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] in the United States. It has sold over 16 million copies worldwide<ref name=cmm>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/music/music-news/avril-lavigne-madonna-is-my-idol-1091758|title=Avril Lavigne: Madonna is my idol |work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|author=Rick Fulton|date=January 10, 2011|accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> and is [[RIAA certification|certified]] seven-times platinum in the United States.<ref name=\"RIAA\"/> The album's lead single, \"[[Complicated (Avril Lavigne song)|Complicated]]\", peaked at number one in Australia and Canada and at number two in the United States. Its subsequent single releases, \"[[Sk8er Boi]]\" and \"[[I'm with You (Avril Lavigne song)|I'm with You]]\", became worldwide top ten hits. Lavigne released her second studio album ''[[Under My Skin (Avril Lavigne album)|Under My Skin]]'' in May 2004, and debuted at number one in Australia, Mexico, Canada, Japan, the United Kingdom and the United States. The album went on to sell more than 10 million copies worldwide.<ref name=\"cmm\"/> \"[[My Happy Ending]]\", the second and most successful single from the album, peaked at number nine on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and sold 1.2 million copies in the United States.<ref name=\"ask billboard15\">{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6685941/ask-billboard-avril-lavignes-best-selling-songs-albums |last=Trust |first=Gary |title=Ask Billboard: Avril Lavigne's Best-Selling Songs & Albums |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=September 6, 2015 |accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2007, her third studio album, ''[[The Best Damn Thing]]'', was released. It was her second album to debut at number one on the US ''Billboard'' 200 chart and has produced Lavigne's most successful single, \"[[Girlfriend (Avril Lavigne song)|Girlfriend]]\". The song became her first number one hit on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart, and subsequently became her best-selling single in that region with 3.8 million copies sold.<ref name=\"ask billboard15\"/> The song also peaked at number one on the other record charts of several nations, including Canada, Australia, New Zealand and Europe. Totally, \"Girlfriend\" became the worldwide best-selling single of 2007, with 7.5 million copies sold.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.ifpi.org/content/library/DMR2008.pdf |title= Digital Music Sales in 2007 |publisher= International Federation of the Phonographic Industry |page= 6 |accessdate= November 13, 2010}}</ref> The album's second single, \"[[When You're Gone (Avril Lavigne song)|When You're Gone]]\", was a top-forty hit in the United States, and it reached the top ten in Australia, Canada, Sweden, and the United Kingdom.\n\nIn March 2011, Lavigne released her fourth studio album, ''[[Goodbye Lullaby]]''. It was preceded by its lead single, \"[[What the Hell]]\", which peaked at number eleven on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 chart and has sold 2.1 million copies in the United States.<ref name=\"ask billboard15\"/> The album's second single, \"[[Smile (Avril Lavigne song)|Smile]]\", was released in May 2011, and its third, \"[[Wish You Were Here (Avril Lavigne song)|Wish You Were Here]]\", was released later in September. In November 2013, Lavigne released her fifth studio album, ''[[Avril Lavigne (album)|Avril Lavigne]]''. Its lead single, \"[[Here's to Never Growing Up]]\", had moderate success peaking inside the top 20 in Australia, Canada, Ireland, the United Kingdom, and the United States, selling 1.3 million copies in the United States.<ref name=\"ask billboard15\"/> The album spawned four more singles: \"[[Rock n Roll (Avril Lavigne song)|Rock n Roll]]\", \"[[Let Me Go (Avril Lavigne song)|Let Me Go]]\", \"[[Hello Kitty (song)|Hello Kitty]]\" and \"[[Give You What You Like]]\".\n\nLavigne has written songs for several film soundtracks, including those of ''[[American Wedding]]'' and ''[[Sweet Home Alabama (film)|Sweet Home Alabama]]''. Two songs that she originally wrote for films were included on subsequent studio albums. \"[[Keep Holding On]]\", written for ''[[Eragon (film)|Eragon]]'', appeared on ''The Best Damn Thing'', and \"[[Alice (Avril Lavigne song)|Alice]]\", written for ''[[Alice in Wonderland (2010 film)|Alice in Wonderland]]'', appeared on ''Goodbye Lullaby''. To date, Lavigne has sold 13 million albums in the United States.<ref name=\"RIAA\"/> Lavigne had sold more than 30 million singles and 40&nbsp;million copies of her albums worldwide.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/avril-lavigne-head-above-water-release-date-new-album-lyme-disease-diagnosis-a8681181.html |title=Avril Lavigne new album Head Above Water gets release date \u2014 her first record since Lyme disease diagnosis |last=Shepherd |first=Jack |work=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cp24.com/avril-lavigne-releases-what-the-hell-lead-single-off-album-goodbye-lullaby-1.594745 |title=Avril Lavigne releases 'What the Hell,' lead single off album, 'Goodbye Lullaby'|author=The Canadian Press |work=[[CP24]]}}</ref> She has 13 vevo certified videos, including \"Girlfriend\", \"Smile\", \"Complicated\" and \"Hot\".\n\n==Albums==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of studio albums, with selected chart positions, sales figures and certifications\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:17em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"10\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\"| Sales\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:13em;\"| [[List of music recording certifications|Certifications]]\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|CAN]]<br><ref name=\"CAN-AL\">{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/avril-lavigne/chart-history/CNA |title=Avril Lavigne Chart History: Canadian Albums |work=Billboard | accessdate=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br><ref name=\"AUS\">{{cite web|url=http://australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Avril+Lavigne|title=Discography Avril Lavigne|work=australian-charts.com|publisher=Hung Medien|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|AUT]]<br><ref name=\"AUT\">{{cite web |url=http://austriancharts.at/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Avril+Lavigne|title=Discographie&nbsp;\u2013 Avril Lavigne|publisher=austriancharts.at, Hung Medien|location=Austria|language=German|accessdate=March 17, 2012}}</ref> \n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[GfK Entertainment Charts|GER]]<br><ref name=\"GER\">{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/suche?artist_search=Avril+Lavigne&do_search=do|title=Discographie Avril Lavigne|publisher=GfK Entertainment|accessdate=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col